I am a 100% Service-Connected Disabled Army combat Veteran, with a desire to continue to learn and earn degrees in my areas of interest in the hopes of finding a way to use them... but I don't have the financial means to pay for education anymore, and my disabilities limit my ability to work, which has left me as a Self-Employed disabled veteran, so that I can schedule what work I can do, when I am best able to do it. I somehow came across this opportunity and my love of cooking coupled with the "Harvard" name and the right price of "FREE", and I knew it was meant for me!  

Plus, the bonus is seeing that a certificate comes with it... which I would be proud to not only hang on my wall and use as my Facebook cover picture, but it is a program that I can write about as I go through it. 

My BA, with a concentration in Literature, Writing, & Editing (LWE) comes from North Carolina State University, 1989, and is equivalent to the University of North Carolina's degree in journalism.  State schools in NC were not allowed to have the "same" titled course at that time.  My minor was in Business & Personnel Management.

Hence, my desire to chronicle my learning venture with edX program... if that's okay with edX and the many fine participating schools providing this opportunity.

goals:
Looking ahead at what is coming in the next month makes reality sink in. My experience as a veterinarian working with the mountain Gorillas, people around the national parks through USAID/PREDICT project showed me that there is a big global challenge in environmental change and human health, especially at the human-wildlife interface, which may soon expand across the line. As I saw from the course outcome, I became so much interested because it would help me in addressing issues related to human health and environmental change. 
The course would specifically help me attain the following objectives;
-Understand major forces that influence the health of individuals and populations nationally, regionally and internationally.
-Have a basic understanding of the complexity of global health and environmental change
-Be able to identify sources of information concerning environmental change and human health
-Be able to articulate the role of physicians as advocates for improving the health of patients and populations in their communities and around the world.
-Acquire skills, knowledge and capacity to manage and guide appropriately in global health and environmental issues 
-To gain knowledge to critique and evaluate the impact of the existing national and international disease control programs on human health and environmental change
-Above all to share my experience and hear from the rest.
